In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims September 27, 2010, as Family Day in the United States. He emphasizes the importance of committed families in shaping and guiding children, preparing them for challenges and helping them overcome negative influences such as drug and alcohol abuse. The President encourages parents, loved ones, and mentors to educate youth about the risks they face and promote positive and healthy behaviors. He acknowledges the demanding responsibilities of parents and urges them to spend valuable time with their children. President Obama also highlights the role of concerned and active parents in keeping children drug-free, suggesting that leading by example and engaging in simple activities like sharing meals, conversations, or books can have a significant impact on a child's life. He calls upon the American people to observe Family Day by spending time with their families and participating in appropriate ceremonies and activities to honor and strengthen the nation's families.